A study by the Portuguese Society of Gynecology revealed that 83.4% of 15-to-19-year-old women received contraceptive information at school.
The study surveyed 3,858 women aged 15-49, highlighting that 16% of sexually active teens in Portugal do not use any birth control.
Nearly one-third of sexually active Portuguese girls aged 15-19 have used the morning-after pill.
The pill, containing levonorgestrel, prevents pregnancy by inhibiting ovulation.
Access to emergency contraception can reduce teen pregnancies without impacting sexual behavior.
